\section{Appendix C: Moving-Mirror Analogue with Memory}
\label{app:moving_mirror}
We now expand the moving-mirror analogue with an explicit construction that mirrors the HMC influence-functional structure. Consider a (1+1)D conformal field with a boundary trajectory $x=f(u)$ imposing a Robin-type boundary condition with an integro-differential term:
\[
\partial_x \phi|_{x=f(u)} + \int_{-\infty}^{u} du'\; \Xi^R(u-u')\,\phi(u',f(u')) \;=\; 0.
\]
This boundary condition is the analogue of coupling exterior matter dressings to edge-mode memory. The kernel $\Xi^R$ is causal and satisfies KMS at an effective temperature set by the asymptotic mirror acceleration (Unruh temperature). The Wightman function is modified by the influence functional
\[
\mathcal{F}[\phi_+,\phi_-] = \exp\Big\{ i \int du\,du'\, (\phi_+ - \phi_-)\Xi^R(\phi_+ + \phi_-)/2 - \tfrac12\int du\,du' (\phi_+ - \phi_-)N(\phi_+ - \phi_-) \Big\},
\]
with $N$ fixed by FDT. The emission spectrum remains thermal at leading order; the kernel generates comb sidebands in the intensity correlator $g^{(2)}(\Delta u)$ with amplitude $\sim O(1/S_{\rm BH}^{\rm eff})$ and correlation time $\tau_{\rm mem}\sim \beta \log S_{\rm BH}^{\rm eff}$. 

Experimental protocol:
- Calibrate mirror trajectory to produce a steady thermal spectrum (baseline).
- Introduce weak, controlled “memory” via an engineered boundary circuit (optomechanical or electronic feedback) implementing a discretized $\Xi^R$.
- Measure $g^{(2)}(\Delta u)$ via homodyne/heterodyne detection; fit to kernel families constrained by causality/KMS.
- Null-test with off-retarded windows and phase scrambling. 

Parameter identification:
- Fit $(\alpha_j,\Gamma_j,\Omega_j)$ in a discrete expansion $\Xi^R(t)=\sum_j \alpha_j e^{-\Gamma_j t}\cos\Omega_j t\,\Theta(t)$ subject to $\alpha_j\ge 0$ and KMS/causality constraints. 
This gives a controlled lab proxy for kernel tomography under the same physical constraints as HMC.

\section{Appendix D: Schwarzian Correlators and the Memory Kernel}
\label{app:schwarzian_appendix}
We provide additional details on the Schwarzian derivation. Starting with JT gravity and boundary reparameterization $t\mapsto f(t)$ with action $S=\frac{C}{2}\int dt\,\{f,t\}$, expand around $f(t)=t+\epsilon(t)$ to quadratic order. The boundary stress-energy two-point function $\langle T(t)T(0)\rangle$ determines the linear response to an external coupling $g\,\phi(t)$, and the retarded kernel reads
\[
\Xi^R(\omega)=\frac{g^2}{C}\left[\psi\!\left(1+\frac{i \beta \omega}{2\pi}\right)+\psi\!\left(1-\frac{i \beta \omega}{2\pi}\right)-2\psi(1)\right] + O(C^{-2}),
\]
analytic in the upper half-plane (causality). Low-frequency behavior includes dissipative and logarithmic memory terms:
\[
\Xi^R(\omega)\sim \frac{g^2}{C}\left[c_0 + c_2\,\omega^2 \log\!\left(\frac{\omega}{\kappa}\right) + i\pi\,\omega\,\mathrm{sgn}\,\omega + \cdots \right].
\]
Greybody dressing in 4D introduces $\Gamma_\ell(\omega)$ and mild logarithms from near-horizon matching as in Eq.~\eqref{eq:kernel_4d}. The amplitude $\propto 1/C\sim 1/S_{\rm BH}$ ensures gentleness, while the long memory produces the retarded sidebands that we target observationally.

\section{Appendix E: Code Availability, Seeding, and Reproducibility}
\label{app:code}
We provide a deterministic utility that generates all inline datasets, including the new PT--MPO large-scale Page curves and resource tables (v6). Seeds are recorded in a JSON ledger. The PT--MPO surrogate data implements finite-memory-depth compression with certified small discarded weights and frame-potential audits in line with Prop.~\ref{prop:error}. All arrays can be exported for independent PGFPlots ingestion.

\section{Appendix F: Data Availability}
All figures and tables are generated from deterministic, inline datasets included in this LaTeX source to ensure compilation without external dependencies. The companion script outputs statistically consistent datasets (and the specific ledger used here). Numerical parameters for PT--MPO surrogates are included in Tab.~\ref{tab:ptmpo_scaling}.

